{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17641111","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17641111"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:24:02+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:24:02+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17865"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17865","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17865"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.05,0.91,0.02,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10579"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115352"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10579","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10579"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17865"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97355"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4929"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10475"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24660"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24663"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115352","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/115352"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the function of fatty acid transport proteins?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Transport glucose across cell membranes","Facilitate cholesterol synthesis","Facilitate free fatty acid uptake into cells","Convert fatty acids to triglycerides","Regulate insulin secretion"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFacilitate free fatty acid uptake into cells\u003C/strong\u003E is correct as FATP are integral membrane proteins that transport long-chain fatty acids across the plasma membrane, enabling their utilisation for energy production or storage.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETransport glucose across cell membranes\u003C/strong\u003E is the function of glucose transporters (GLUT), not FATP. \u003Cstrong\u003EFacilitate cholesterol synthesis\u003C/strong\u003E involves different enzymes within cells, not FATP. \u003Cstrong\u003EConvert fatty acids to triglycerides\u003C/strong\u003E is performed by other enzymes within the cell after fatty acid uptake has occurred. \u003Cstrong\u003ERegulate insulin secretion\u003C/strong\u003E is not a direct function of FATP.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFATP are particularly abundant in tissues with high fatty acid metabolism, such as adipose tissue, skeletal muscle, and liver. Their expression and activity are not directly regulated by insulin, unlike glucose transporters.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Fatty acid transport proteins (FATP) facilitate the uptake of long-chain fatty acids across cell membranes.","FATP are highly expressed in metabolically active tissues like adipose tissue, skeletal muscle and liver.","Unlike glucose transporters, FATP activity is not directly regulated by insulin signalling."],"references":["Bender DA, Cunningham SM. Introduction to nutrition and metabolism. CRC Press; 2021.","Salway JG. Metabolism at a Glance. John Wiley \u0026 Sons; 2016.","Chandel NS. Lipid Metabolism. Cold Spring Harb Perspect Biol. 2021 Sep 1;13(9):a040576. doi: 10.1101/cshperspect.a040576. PMID: 34470787; PMCID: PMC8411952.","Wakil SJ, Abu-Elheiga LA. Fatty acid metabolism: target for metabolic syndrome. J Lipid Res. 2009 Apr;50 Suppl(Suppl):S138-43. doi: 10.1194/jlr.R800079-JLR200. Epub 2008 Dec 1. PMID: 19047759; PMCID: PMC2674721."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97355"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17865"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97355","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/97355"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-23T12:42:06+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-23T12:42:06+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10579"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115352"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4926","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4926"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiovascular","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:14:59+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-31T09:50:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"13"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},